{{italic title}}  
[[File:Edouard_Manet_031.jpg|thumb]]
'''''Chez le père Lathuille''''' (''At the Père Lathuille Restaurant'') is an 1879 oil on canvas painting by [[Édouard Manet]], now in the [[Musée des Beaux-Arts Tournai]]. He painted it just before his death and signed it "Manet, 1879". In the background is the proprietor - Manet also painted [[Portrait of Marguerite Gauthier-Lathuille |a portrait]] of his daughter.

Père Lathuille's cabaret and later restaurant was sited in the [[Batignolles]] quarter, on the site now occupied by a cinema at 7 Avenue de Clichy, just after the Barrière de Clichy so as to escape Parisian wine taxes. During the [[Battle of Paris (1814)|defence of Paris]] on 30 March 1814 marshal [[Bon-Adrien Jeannot de Moncey]] had used it as his command post. Just before the enemy arrived, Père Lathuille had handed out free drinks to the soldiers, saying "Drink, my friends, drink for free - don't leave a single bottle of my wine in the casks".

