{{Infobox NRHP | name = Mary Schenley Memorial Fountain | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes | partof = Schenley Farms Historic District | partof_refnum = 83002213<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> | image = Schenley Fountain.JPG | caption = The Mary Schenley Memorial Fountain in front of the [[Frick Fine Arts Building]] | location = [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States|USA]] | nearest_city = | coordinates = {{coord|40|26|31.18|N|79|57|06.82|W|display=inline,title}} | area = [[Schenley Farms Historic District]] | built = 1918 | architect = [[Victor David Brenner]] | architecture = | added = July 22, 1983 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[Pittsburgh, PA|City of Pittsburgh]] }} The '''Mary Schenley Memorial Fountain''', also known as '''''A Song to Nature''''', is a 1918 landmark public sculpture in bronze and granite by [[Victor David Brenner]]. It sits in [[Schenley Plaza]] at the entrance to [[Schenley Park]] and directly in front of the [[University of Pittsburgh]]'s [[Frick Fine Arts Building]] in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]. The fountain is designated as a contributing property to the [[Schenley Farms Historic District]].<ref>[http://mac10.umc.pitt.edu/u/FMPro?-db=ustory&-format=d.html&-lay=a&-sortfield=issueid%3a%3aissuedate&-sortorder=descend&keywords=bellefield%20hall&-max=50&-recid=38544&-find= University Times<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090628170337/http://mac10.umc.pitt.edu/u/FMPro?-db=ustory&-format=d.html&-lay=a&-sortfield=issueid%3A%3Aissuedate&-sortorder=descend&keywords=bellefield%20hall&-max=50&-recid=38544&-find= |date=2009-06-28 }}</ref>
The work of art comprises two major figures: a reclining [[Pan (mythology)|Pan]], the [[Greek god]] of shepherds, and above him a female singer playing a [[lyre]]. From crevices along the fountain's rim four turtles spew water into the basin. An inscription on the pedestal reads, "A Song of Nature, Pan the Earth God Answers to the Harmony and Magic Tones Sung to the Lyre by Sweet Humanity." The basin of the fountain is 15 feet high, above which the figures rise another 15 feet.
The fountain honors [[Mary Schenley]]. In 1889, after intensive lobbying by [[Edward Manning Bigelow]], director of parks for the City of Pittsburgh, Schenley donated the land for the park named in her honor. Upon her death, Pittsburgh City Council sponsored a national competition for the memorial. The judges selected this design by Brenner, who is famous today for his design of the [[Penny (United States coin)|Lincoln cent]], which is still in circulation.
In June 2008, restoration efforts were begun that include repairs, cleaning, plumbing, paving, and landscaping. A gift from the Benter Foundation will provide lighting for the fountain and plaza.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/search/s_580089.html | title=Repairs under way on Schenley fountain | publisher = Pittsburgh Tribune-Review | date=2008-07-30 | accessdate=2008-08-05}}</ref>
